<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
                    xmlns:sys="clr-namespace:System;assembly=System.Runtime">

  <!--
    Motion tokens per project_design_guide.md §8.1.

    Token vs Use:
      Motion.Instant   0 ms     reduce-motion fallback target (§8.4)
      Motion.Fast    120 ms     hover state changes, button press
      Motion.Default 240 ms     tab switch fade, modal fade-in
      Motion.Slow    400 ms     toast slide-in, page transitions

    Format: "h:mm:ss.fff" — consumers parse via WPF's DurationConverter.

    Why strings, not <Duration> elements: Duration has no parameterless
    constructor that XAML can use directly. Strings + the consumer's
    DurationConverter is the path of least resistance.

    Important: Storyboard.Duration assignments inside ControlTemplate
    triggers (Buttons.xaml press scale, CheckBox.xaml tick) cannot
    reference these tokens via DynamicResource — WPF's ControlTemplate
    sealing tries to freeze its Storyboard tree, and DynamicResource
    references prevent freezing ("Cannot freeze this Storyboard
    timeline tree for use across threads"). StaticResource is the
    other option but breaks the standalone-XAML-load path used by
    snapshot tests. So the templates inline their durations as
    literals (with §8.1 comments) and these tokens are consumed only
    by code-behind animation paths (TransitioningContentControl,
    RevealablePasswordBox); ReduceMotion.For() routes them through
    the §8.4 fallback. ApplyToApplicationResources shadows these
    keys at startup if the OS preference is off so future
    code-behind consumers can rely on the same token surface.

    Spring (§8.1 last entry) is intentionally not a token here —
    spring physics in WPF live in PowerEase / BackEase / ElasticEase
    parameter combinations, not a Duration scalar; consumers wire
    them inline next to the storyboard they belong to.
  -->

  <sys:String x:Key="Motion.Instant">0:0:0</sys:String>
  <sys:String x:Key="Motion.Fast">0:0:0.12</sys:String>
  <sys:String x:Key="Motion.Default">0:0:0.24</sys:String>
  <sys:String x:Key="Motion.Slow">0:0:0.4</sys:String>

</ResourceDictionary>
